{{see also|:fr:Vladimir Nicolaievitch Orloff}} [[File:1903 ball - Orlov.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Prince Orlov in 1903 dressed for a fancy ball.]] Prince '''Vladimir Nikolayevich Orlov''' (Dec. 31, 1868-Aug. 29, 1927), one of the [[Orlov (family)]], was one of [[Tsar Nicholas II]]'s closest advisors,<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=RhXyCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA259&lpg=PA259 Douglas Smith: "Rasputin: Faith, Power, and the Twilight of the Romanovs"] Farrar, Straus and Giroux 2016</ref><ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=T3botnZZRfwC&pg=PA53 "The Last Diary of Tsaritsa Alexandra"], Yale, 1997</ref><ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=YIhU7RWPFBYC&pg=PT150&lpg=PT150 Julia P. Gelardi: "From Splendor to Revolution: The Romanov Women, 1847--1928"] St. Martin's Press, 2011</ref> and between 1906 and 1915 headed the Tsar's military cabinet.<ref name=alix/><ref name=ham/>
==Biography== [[File:Valentin Serov - Portrait of Princess Olga Orlova - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[:ru:Портрет княгини Ольги Орловой|1911 portrait of Olga Orlov]] by [[Valentin Serov]].]] Orlov, who bore the nickname "Fat Orlov",<ref>[[Simon Sebag Montefiore]]: [https://books.google.ca/books?id=o9RfCgAAQBAJ&pg=PR82 "The Romanovs: 1613-1918"] Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group, 2016</ref><ref name=alix>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=hv_etSixIBwC&pg=PT229 Virginia Rounding: "Alix and Nicky: The Passion of the Last Tsar and Tsarina"] St. Martin's Press, 2012</ref> may have introduced to the Tsar the motorcar in 1903,<ref>[http://www.alexanderpalace.org/palace/impgarage.html "WMF Report - The Imperial Garage - the Tsar and His Cars"]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=TLMOBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA238 Helen Nicholas: "Maelstrom"], 2011</ref> and was married to Olga, a daughter of Prince [[Constantine Esperovich Beloselsky-Belozersky]].<ref name=ham>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=qQmjAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT195 Paul Ham: "1914 The Year The World Ended"], Random House, 2014</ref> His son [[Prince Nicholas Vladimirovich Orlov]] (1891–1961) wed in 1917 [[Princess Nadejda Petrovna of Russia|Nadezhda Petrovna Romanov Orloff]].
===Patron of engineers=== [[File:Kegresse pt1913.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Drawing from the 1913 patent of the Kégresse half-track.]] As the head of the military cabinet, Orlov was a keen technologist interested in military applications of the motor car. He was the patron of [[Adolphe Kégresse]], the brilliant mechanical engineer responsible for the [[Kégresse track]]. Orlov wrote in a letter to the Tsar on 15 May 1914:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alexanderpalace.org/palace/impgarage.html |title=The Imperial Garage - the Tsar and His Cars |df=dmy }}</ref> {{cquote|... I consider Kegress an irreplaceable worker and I am afraid his leaving will be a great loss for the garage. Your Highness knows, of course, how much His Majesty appreciates Kegress.}} Indeed, Kégresse continued as Head of the Mechanical Department of the [[Russian Imperial Garage]] at [[Tsarskoye Selo]] until the fall of the Romanovs caused him to flee to his homeland.
===Fall over Rasputin=== Orlov continued his military duties until he was banished by the Tsar in 1915 to the Caucasus after losing the struggle for power to [[Rasputin]]. On August 19, 1915, after an unsuccessful attempt to discredit Rasputin and the Tsarina in a newspaper he and [[Vladimir Dzhunkovsky]], First Deputy Interior Minister, were discharged from their posts,<ref name=mad>[http://worldhistory-photos.blogspot.ca/2014/05/rasputin.html "Grigori Rasputin, the 'mad monk'"]</ref> and four days later, the Tsar took supreme command of the Russian armies fighting on the [[Eastern Front (World War I)|Eastern Front of the First World War]].<ref name=mad/><ref>[https://wwi.lib.byu.edu/index.php/An_Ambassador's_Memoirs F. A. HOLT, ed (1925) "AN AMBASSADOR'S MEMOIRS"] By [[Maurice Paléologue]]</ref> As ''[[London Times]]'' correspondent [[Robert Wilton]] put it,<ref>[http://ww1blog.osborneink.com/?p=10110]</ref> {{cquote|The loathsome Rasputin played no small part in suggesting the Tsar’s mystical motives for taking up the High Command. Rasputin always works in the same way. He tells the Empress that he had a vision that certain things must be done, the Empress then retails this stuff to her husband and the trick is done. It reminds one of the Byzantine Court.}}
===In exile=== Orlov, exiled by events subsequent to the [[Russian revolution of 1917]], was buried in Paris, France.<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/or/vladimir-prince-orlov-1.html "https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/or/vladimir-prince-orlov-1.html"]</ref><ref name=fag>[https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=105051223 findagrave.com: "Vladimir Nikolaevich Orlov"]</ref>
