{{Women in society sidebar}}
'''Women in Peru''' represent a minority in both numbers and legal rights. Although historically somewhat equal to men, after the Spanish conquest the culture in what is now Peru became increasingly [[patriarchy|patriarchal]]. The patriarchal culture is still noticeable. Women receive less pay than men, have fewer employment and political opportunities, and are at times abused without repercussion.{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}} [[Contraceptive]] availability is not enough for the demand, and over a third of pregnancies end in [[abortion]]. Maternal death rates are also some of the highest in South America.{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}}

The [[Government of Peru|Peruvian Government]] has begun efforts to combat the high maternal mortality rate and lack of female political representation, as well as [[violence against women]]. However, the efforts have not yet borne fruit.

==History==
[[Andean civilizations|Andean civilization]] is traditionally somewhat egalitarian for men and women, with women allowed to inherit property from their mothers. After the [[Spanish conquest of the Inca Empire|Spanish conquered]] the [[Inca Empire]], the culture became more patriarchal; and the resulting society has been described as being ''[[machista]]''.{{sfn|Barrett|2002|p=83}}{{sfn|Crabtree|2002|p=11}}

During the republican revolutions in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries, the concept of separate spheres (private vs. public) became a legally debated issue in Peru.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Habermas|first1=Jurgen|title=The Structural Transformation of the Public Sphere|date=1989|publisher=MIT Press|location=Cambridge}}</ref> Determining a clear distinction of the boundaries between private crimes and public crimes became significant because only public crimes could be directly prosecuted by the state.<ref name="auto">{{cite book|last1=Caulfield|first1=Sueann|last2=Chambers|first2=Sarah|last3=Putnam|first3=Lara|title=Honor, Status, and Law in Modern America|date=2005|publisher=Duke University Press|pages=27}}</ref> During this time, public crimes were crimes that affected the state or society, while private crimes only harmed the individual committing the act. Although all civil cases were considered to be private, some private crimes could potentially affect the public.<ref name="auto"/> Crimes such as theft and inflicting serious bodily injuries had previously only been prosecuted by the wishes of the plaintiff; however, during the early republic, these crimes were pursued based on the prosecutors’ and judges’ own agendas.<ref name="auto"/> In contrast, crimes such as slander, rape, or anything related to honor was treated the same as before. Victims of these crimes had to do substantially more work than victims of theft and serious physical injuries.<ref name="auto1">{{cite book|last1=Caulfield|first1=Sueann|last2=Chambers|first2=Sarah|last3=Putnam|first3=Lara|title=Honor, Status, and Law in Modern America|date=2005|publisher=Duke University Press|pages=27–28}}</ref> In order for their case to be considered, these victims had to report their cases themselves, and had to file a formal complaint as well as provide witnesses. These plaintiff were expected to decide whether the crime itself or reporting the crime to the court would create greater harm to their honor.<ref name="auto1"/> 

Even though there could be circumstances in which rape or seduction would disturb society enough to make it a public crime, to give prosecutors the power to file charges would "disturb the peace and secrecy that should exist in the domestic sphere." For the same reason, physical injuries resulting from the "punishment" of dependence (servants, wives, children) were usually considered "private", crimes and the rights of the perpetrators carried more weight than the protections due to the victims, who were not, after all, citizens. Even as republican judicial officials tried to balance the demands of public and domestic order, they continue to trend, begun with the Bourbon reforms, of increasingly claiming jurisdiction in those cases pertaining to marriage, family, and sexual honor, in which the affected parties did press charges. Formerly, such cases had fallen primarily within the jurisdiction of the church.<ref name="auto1"/>

During this republican state, men who were contributed to the public sphere and were either married, between the age of 21 and 25, owned property, had an independent profession, or paid taxes were granted “citizenship status.” <ref>{{cite book|last1=Caulfield|first1=Sueann|last2=Chambers|first2=Sarah|last3=Putnam|first3=Lara|title=Honor, Status, and Law in Modern America|date=2005|publisher=Duke University Press|pages=29}}</ref> This enabled them to easily obtain protection of their civil liberties. Women, on the other hand, did not receive the same benefits because their roles were confided to the private sphere. The labor traditionally done by women (sewing, cooking, child-rearing, etc.) became worthless because it was no longer recognized as a public contribution, but just a part of the private (patriarchal) system in Peru. Legally, women held little protections, as it was seen as their husband or father's job to protect them.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Chambers|first1=Sarah|title=Honor, Status, and Law in Modern Latin America|date=2005|publisher=Duke University Press|location=Durham|pages=27–49}}</ref> 

Legally, women were not protected by the new system. As a result of this, they faced many hardships. For example, domestic abuse was an ongoing problem mainly because abuse and rape were considered to be “private crimes.” The state classified these heinous acts this way because they did not want to disrupt the male patriarchal society.

Women were mainly defined by their sexuality purity and domestic serving abilities. Poor women, in particular, had a hard time conforming to the “republican mother” look and could not base claims on their rights or duties as mothers.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Caulfield|first1=Sueann|last2=Chambers|first2=Sarah|last3=Putnam|first3=Lara|title=Honor, Status, and Law in Modern America|date=2005|publisher=Duke University Press|pages=35}}</ref> Furthermore, if they were convicted of a crime, they were seen as “unnatural” and were often prevented from being released early from prison.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Caulfield|first1=Sueann|last2=Chambers|first2=Sarah|last3=Putnam|first3=Lara|title=Honor, Status, and Law in Modern America|date=2005|publisher=Duke University Press|pages=37}}</ref> Although women like Maria Toledo and Juana Pia fought to be released early because of good behavior and because they were the sole supporter of their children, the prosecutor argued that the women would negatively influence their children. On the contrary, men were seen as the hard working provider for the family and received more advantages than women. For example, a few months before Toledo’s petition was denied, an “honorable man’s” sentence was reduced because his wife had indicated on the appeal that he was her family’s sole provider.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Caulfield|first1=Sueann|last2=Chambers|first2=Sarah|last3=Putnam|first3=Lara|title=Honor, Status, and Law in Modern America|date=2005|publisher=Duke University Press|pages=36}}</ref>

This misogynist system prevailed for many decades.  

On June 17, 1956, Peruvian women voted for the first time in general elections, after years of mobilization by women like María Jesús Alvarado, Adela Montesinos, Zoila Aurora Cáceres, Elvira García y García, and Magda Portal, among others. Peru was the next-to-last country in Latin America to fully enfranchise women.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elperuano.pe/noticia-el-voto-femenino-el-peru-56802.aspx|title=El voto femenino en el Perú|website=elperuano.pe|language=es|access-date=2018-07-16}}</ref> 

During the [[internal conflict in Peru]] beginning in the 1980s, some families became matriarchal, with approximately 78 percent of migrant families being headed by women. In shantytowns, women established [[soup kitchen]]s (''comedores'') and worked together to ensure that their families  received enough food to eat.{{sfn|Barrett|2002|p=83}}{{sfn|Crabtree|2002|p=46}}

The abuses during the conflict have caused both mental and physical problems in women. Identification papers, necessary for the execution of civil rights like voting, were also destroyed ''en masse''. {{as of|2007}}, approximately 18.1 percent of Peruvian women are living without the necessary documents, as opposed to 12.2 percent of men.{{sfn|Amnesty International|2009|pp=26-27}} Even today, women from indigenous tribes may be treated disrespectfully by authority figures. The same applies to poor women.{{sfn|Amnesty International|2009|p=22}} 

In ninetieth century Peru, women were treated as if their lives had been divided in two different ways.  One part of a woman’s life was considered private which included the work that women did and how they were treated inside the home.  By declaring the work that women do as private, this then lowers their status in Peru being their work was not valued.  Private work was not a way for women to gain a larger role of independence.  The other part of a woman’s life was considered public, and in this case it was hard for women to fulfill a large amount of public activity. Public activity for women was a tough area being that women’s work was worthless therefore, they were not important in the community.<ref>Mentioned in, Caulfield, Sueann, et al. “Private Crimes, Public Order: Honor, Gender, and the Law in Early Republican Peru.” Honor, Status, and Law in Modern Latin America, Duke University Press, 2005, pp. 33–37.</ref>

==Forced sterilization==
Forced sterilization against indigenous and poor women has been practiced on a large scale in Peru. The Final Report of the [[Truth and Reconciliation Commission (Peru)|Truth and Reconciliation Commission]], published in 2003, notes that during the internal conflict in Peru, there were numerous cases of women being [[Compulsory sterilization|forcibly sterilized]] - also, another estimated up to 300,000 mostly rural women were sterilised under deception or with insufficient consent in the 1990s as part of a campaign intended to combat poverty.<ref>{{cite news|title=Peru Forcibly Sterilized 300,000 Poor Women in the '90s. Now They Could Decide the Country's Future.|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/120427/campaign-300000-peruvian-women-sterilized-against-their-will|accessdate=28 November 2014|work=The New Republic|date=26 November 2014}}</ref>

President [[Alberto Fujimori]] (in office from 1990–2000) has been accused of [[genocide]] and [[crimes against humanity]] as a result of a sterilization program put in place by his administration. During his presidency, Fujimori conducted a program of forced sterilizations against indigenous [[Quechua people|Quechuas]] and the [[Aymara people|Aymaras]] women, under the guise of a "[[public health]] plan".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/2148793.stm|title=Mass sterilisation scandal shocks Peru|author=|date=24 July 2002|publisher=|accessdate=17 April 2018|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.monde-diplomatique.fr/2004/05/BARTHELEMY/11190|title=Stérilisations forcées des Indiennes du Pérou|author=|date=1 May 2004|website=monde-diplomatique.fr|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref>

==Education==
[[File:School girls from Cusco, Peru.jpg|thumb|250 px|School girls in Peru]]
Female literacy is lower than male literacy in Peru: only 94.3% of females (15 and older) are literate, compared to 97.2% of males, according to 2016 estimates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2103.html|title=The World Factbook — Central Intelligence Agency|author=|date=|website=www.cia.gov|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref>

Indigenous women of Peru travel less than men. As such, they tend to be less fluent in Spanish, the national language of Peru. This may lead to difficulties when they must speak with outsiders, who often do not speak the indigenous language.{{sfn|Amnesty International|2009|p=22}} Although women have a higher illiteracy rate than men, an increasing number of women are receiving higher education.{{sfn|Barrett|2002|p=83}}

==Demographics==
Women are a slight minority in Peru; in 2010 they represented 49.9 percent of the population. Women have a life expectancy of 74 years at birth, five years more than men.{{sfn|OECD|2010|p=128}}

Latest estimates suggest that the population of Peru is Amerindian 45%, mestizo (mixed Amerindian and white) 37%, white 15%, black, Japanese, Chinese, and other 3%.<ref name="cia.gov">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/pe.html|title=The World Factbook — Central Intelligence Agency|author=|date=|website=www.cia.gov|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref> More than 8 out of 10 people are Catholics.<ref name="cia.gov"/>

Although Peru has an ethnically diverse population, discrimination by ethnic lines is common, particularly against amerindians and blacks; gender often interacts with ethnic origin; this may mean that "an indigenous woman may only ever work as a maid".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/10205171|title=Peru's minorities battle racism|first=Dan|last=Collyns|date=13 June 2010|publisher=|accessdate=17 April 2018|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>

==Maternal and reproductive health==
[[File:Quechuawomanandchild.jpg|thumb|Quechua woman and child in the [[Sacred Valley]], Peru]]
Women who live in poverty are less likely to give birth in a health center or be attended by a health care worker.{{sfn|Amnesty International|2009|p=25}} Peru has one of the highest [[maternal death]] rates in South America, with the government noting 185 deaths per 100,000 live births, and the [[United Nations]] estimating the number at 240 per 100,000 live births. In order to combat those high figures, the government released a strategic plan in 2008 to reduce the total to 120 maternal deaths per 100,000 live births.{{sfn|Amnesty International|2009|p=11}}

Of these maternal deaths, 46 percent occur during the first six weeks after birth.{{sfn|Amnesty International|2009|p=20}} [[Amnesty International]] notes that [[economic discrimination]] is one of the factors, with women in affluent areas receiving better health care than those in rural areas. Gender and ethnic discrimination in health care also exist.{{sfn|Amnesty International|2009|p=12}}

[[File:Maternal Deaths in Peru.png|200px|left|alt=Hemorraging (dark blue) is the leading cause of maternal death in Peru|border]]
According to the 2007 census, the causes of maternal death in Peru were as follows:{{sfn|Amnesty International|2009|p=20}}
{{legend|#4074B4|Hemorrhage 40.5%}}
{{legend|#AF3738|Other 23.8%}}
{{legend|#85A548|Pre-eclampsia 18.9%}}
{{legend|#725496|Abortion-related 6.1%}}
{{legend|#44A9C3|Infection 6.1%}}
{{legend|#F88739|Unknown 1.8%}}
{{legend|#8DAAD7|Obstructed birth 0.9%}}
{{clear}}

The [[age of consent]] in [[Peru]] has changed several times during recent years, and has been subject to political debates,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2007/06/22/world/main2970190.shtml |title=Peru Lowers Age Of Consent To 14 |author=Lindsay Goldwert|date=2007-06-22 |work= |publisher=CBS NEWS |accessdate=2009-12-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.congreso.gob.pe/Sicr/Prensa/heraldo.nsf/CNnoticiasanteriores/fc34916372aa85c9052573070053ab5a?OpenDocument |title=Pleno Reconsidero Exoneracion de Sedunda Votacion a Proyecto Sobre Libertad Sexual |date=2007-06-27 |publisher=El Heraldo |language=Spanish |trans-title=House Reconsidered and Excluded Second Vote for Project on Sexual Freedom |accessdate=2010-09-02}}</ref> but today it is fixed at '''14''', regardless of [[gender]] and/or [[sexual orientation]], in accordance with a 2012 decision of the [[Constitutional Court of Peru]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.tc.gob.pe/jurisprudencia/2013/00008-2012-AI.pdf| title = Demanda de inconstitucionalidad interpuesta por diez mil seiscientos nueve ciudadanos contra el artículo 1° de la Ley N° 28704 que modifica el artículo 173°, inciso 3° del Código Penal, sobre delito de violación sexual contra víctima entre 14 y 18 años de edad | language = Spanish | date = 2013-01-07}}</ref> [[Teenage pregnancies]] are not uncommon. They are often the result of rape by a male relative.{{sfn|Crabtree|2002|p=67}}

When giving birth, indigenous mothers may avoid going to clinics due to unfamiliarity with the techniques used. They instead prefer to use traditional practices, with which they are comfortable. {{sfn|Amnesty International|2009|p=22}}The lack of health staff able to speak indigenous languages is also a problem.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amnestyusa.org/our-work/campaigns/demand-dignity/maternal-health-is-a-human-right/maternal-mortality-in-peru|title=Our Work – Amnesty International USA|author=|date=|website=amnestyusa.org|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref>

Although [[contraceptives]] are used  in Peru, they are more common in urban areas. An estimated 13.3 percent of women in rural areas are in need of contraceptives that are unavailable, as opposed to 8.7 percent of urban women.{{sfn|Amnesty International|2009|p=40}} Although [[therapeutic abortion]] is legal,{{sfn|Amnesty International|2009|p=41}} and an estimated 35 percent of pregnancies result in abortion,{{sfn|Crabtree|2002|p=67}} regulation and implementation has been controversial, with the only clear  guidelines (in [[Arequipa Region|Arequipa]]) withdrawn under pressure from anti-abortion groups. There have been instances where mothers have been forced to carry babies to term at large personal risk.{{sfn|Amnesty International|2009|p=41}}

The [[HIV/AIDS]] rate in Peru was estimated in 2012 at 0.4% of adults aged 15–49.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2155rank.html|title=The World Factbook — Central Intelligence Agency|author=|date=|website=www.cia.gov|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref>

==Family life==
[[File:Gwalpaca.jpg|thumb|Girl with her [[alpaca]] near the Plaza de Armas in Cusco, Peru]]
By law, Peruvian women must be 16 years old to marry;{{sfn|OECD|2010|p=128}} prior to 1999, it was 14. A 2004 survey by the [[United Nations]] estimates that 13 percent of women between the ages of 15 and 19 have been married. In marriage, the husband and wife share responsibility for household affairs. In approximately 25% of marriages, finances are handled by the husbands;{{sfn|OECD|2010|p=128}} in some other families the mother is the head of the household.{{sfn|Crabtree|2002|p=11}}
Some ethnic groups, such as the [[Asháninka people|Asháninka]], practice polygamy.{{sfn|Barrett|2002|p=83}}

Despite the fact that married Peruvian men occasionally openly take lovers, divorce is difficult to obtain.{{sfn|Barrett|2002|p=83}} In a divorce, custody of children under the age of seven is generally awarded to the mother. Custody of those over seven is generally awarded by gender. If a parent is deemed unfit, the children can be sent to live with the other parent.{{sfn|OECD|2010|p=129}}

== Domestic violence ==
{{Further|Violence against women in Peru}}
The OECD notes that women in Peru are subject to abuse, with almost half suffering from violence. The most common form of abuse is psychological. There are also reports of [[female genital mutilation]] as a rite of passage during puberty.{{sfn|OECD|2010|p=129}} The government has attempted to address the issues, establishing the National Programme against Family Violence and Abuse in 2001, and passing a law requiring local authorities to deal with [[domestic abuse]] and stipulating punishments for rape and [[spousal rape]].{{sfn|OECD|2010|p=128}} Legal action against perpetrators of abuse is slow and ineffectual.{{sfn|Crabtree|2002|p=67}} In 1999 Peru repealed the law which stated that a rapist would be exonerated, if after the assault he and his victim married.<ref name=Warrick66>{{Cite book | publisher = Ashgate Pub. | isbn = 978-0-7546-7587-7<!-- 0754675874--> | last = Warrick | first = Catherine. | title = Law in the service of legitimacy: Gender and politics in Jordan | location = Farnham, Surrey, England; Burlington, Vt. | year = 2009 | page = 66 }}</ref>

The principal law dealing with domestic violence is ''Ley de Protección frente a la Violencia Familiar'' (Law for Protection from Family Violence).<ref>http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/population/domesticviolence/peru.dv.97.pdf</ref> It was first enacted in 1993, has been strengthened in 1997, and thereafter modified several times, in order to broaden its scope: by 2010, this law had already been amended five times.<ref>http://www.justice.gov/eoir/vll/country/canada_coi/peru/PER103441.FE.pdf</ref>


Some abusive husbands were caught in the general rise in criminal prosecution, particularly when their drunken or violent behavior threatened public as well as domestic order. In 1852, for example, shoemaker Laurencio Salazar was arrested for knocking his wife unconscious.Salazar, on previous occasions not only injured his wife but also killed animals for spite and cut his brother-in-law's hand, was dangerously violent. The republican courts defined vaguely the level of violence necessary to constitute assault in domestic cases. Between 1784 and 1824, there were only two worthy cases filed by mothers ''de parte'' under the category of physical or verbal violence but neither made it till the end. In opposition, about half of accused rapists after independence were convicted despite their efforts. Going further, the penalties for rape convictions were "generally stricter than those for nonsexual assault: several months in jail while performing public labor and/or providing a dowry for the young woman".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Caulfield|first1=Sueann|last2=Chambers|first2=Sarah|last3=Putnam|first3=Lara|title=Honor, Status, and Law in Modern America|date=2005|publisher=Duke University Press|pages=38–39}}</ref>

==Economy==
The majority of rural women work in farming,{{sfn|Barrett|2002|p=83}} or take care of household chores.{{sfn|Crabtree|2002|p=11}} On average, they earn [[Gender pay gap|46 percent less than male workers]].{{sfn|Crabtree|2002|p=10}}

Beginning in the 1990s, women increasingly entered service industries to replace men. They were hired because the employers could pay them less and believed that they would not form unions. During that period, labour rights were revoked for women workers.{{sfn|Crabtree|2002|p=44}}

In 2014, the UN noted that despite the fact that the economy of country was improving, women continued to be discriminated and to suffer violence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telesurtv.net/english/news/UN-Concerned-Over-Violence-Against-Women-in-Peru-20140920-0008.html|title=UN Concerned Over Violence Against Women in Peru|first=|last=teleSUR/js-GF|date=|website=telesurtv.net|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref>

==Gender equality==
[[File:Lima Peru 013 (5664340215).jpg|thumb|A woman in Lima, Peru]]
Discrimination based on gender is forbidden by the government of Peru, and a piece of legislation was passed in 2000 that outlawed discrimination. The [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] (OECD) noted that discrimination is practiced, in particular with regard to women's land rights, and that women in Peru generally have higher levels of poverty and unemployment. Those who have jobs have difficulty holding senior positions. The OECD has rated the degree of gender discrimination in Peru as low on the [[Social Institutions and Gender Index]].{{sfn|OECD|2010|p=128}}

Informal land-dispute resolution systems are common, and rural women are often discriminated.<ref>http://usaidlandtenure.net/sites/default/files/country-profiles/full-reports/USAID_Land_Tenure_Peru_Profile.pdf</ref> Women's access to land is not well protected; in 2002, only 25 percent of land titles were given to women, and under an "informal ownership" system the husband may sell property without his wife's consent.{{sfn|OECD|2010|p=129}} In 2014, new laws have improved the access of indigenous people to land.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/poverty-matters/2011/sep/12/peru-land-rights-indigenous-communities|title=Peru leads the way for Latin America's indigenous communities - Mattia Cabitza|first=Mattia|last=Cabitza|date=12 September 2011|website=the Guardian|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref>

Politically, women in Peru have been subordinated to men and had little power. Twenty percent of those [[Peruvian general election, 2001|elected in 2001]] were women. Female politicians are often from richer families, as women from a lower income bracket must deal with housework.{{sfn|Crabtree|2002|p=33}} Recent laws have required a [[quota share|quota]] of representatives in Congress to be women. Despite this, the levels of women's political representation remain below the 30% quota target.<ref>http://www.idea.int/americas/peru/lima_workshop.cfm</ref> As of 2014, there were 22.3% women in parliament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ipu.org/wmn-e/classif.htm|title=Women in Parliaments: World Classification|author=|date=|website=www.ipu.org|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref>

